- in javascript, the primitive types store their values directly in the variables.
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Car Dropdown Menu</title>
</head>
<body>
    <script>
        var cust_name= "sanvi";
        var balance= "30cr";
        var x, y;
        var isvalid =true;
        document.write(cust_name);
        document.write(balance);
        document.write(isvalid);
        document.write(x,y);
    </script>
    
</body>
</html>

- in order to know the type of data of a particular variable at runtime, simply use the operator 'typeof'
document.write(typeof cust_name+"<br>");
- typeof works well on all datatypes except NULL. so, in order to find out whether it is null, use '===' comparison operator. it will return True. 
This operator not only compares the values but the data types too and hence help identify NULL!
- the '==' operator converts athe datatypes and just sompare the values. Basically, if the value is same but datatypes are different, yhen also we will get 'True'.
